content.description: Stem and jam fists/feets up the off-widthy crack until it makes sense to move right onto the face below the anchor shared with "The MInnow", K Keith states that it's 5.6 if you finish on the high ledge to the L via the S wall.NOTE: I'm deferring to the rating given in the guidebook, in keeping with local standards, but I am going to go on the record here as having stated that I think this is "at least" a decimal higher than .4.
content.protection: Probably fat cams/hexes (gasp!), biggish stoppers. Don't take my word for it I didn't place any gear. Use the eyeballs.
content.location: On the west wall of The Parking Lot Rocks, a few feet left of "The Minnow" just inside the large chimney that cleaves the W face.

content.description: Short but fun movement, and thought provoking for the grade!
content.location: The north-facing featured face to the right of Crac-Man.

content.description: Chimney up the chimney (imagine that!) until you wish to abandon it in favor of the face.NOTE: I started up this, but about 3/4 of the way up I decided to polish the edge on my downclimbing skillset. Therefore, I don't know what you'll find at the top. The guidebook doesn't show an anchor or give a written description indicating how one descends. Maybe there's a walk-off or anchors, but I don't know.
content.protection: I didn't find any. None, but what can I say? I wasn't leading it. Use the eyeball and make your own judgements.
content.location: Starts in the big chimney that cleaves the west face.

content.description: Start is pretty tricky on fingertips, then the crack gets really solid as it widens to hands and eventually jugs to pull on to the ledge.Â  Clip a bolt from the ledge and make the slab move to the anchors.
content.protection: Minimum BD 0.3 - 0.75 (or similar) and at least one draw for the bolt. A 0.1 and 0.2 will make the start feel safer.
content.location: Splits the west-facing side of the parking lot rocks.

content.description: The group of cliffs next to the Flume Trail parking area. This crag consists of two faces: The north face and the west face.
